From 8381a630d399fb1289ad05da21b040fc8f18d0ef Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Anshul Dubela <adubela@marvell.com>
Date: Tue, 11 Nov 2025 13:34:36 +0530
Subject: [PATCH] EVPN continues advertising MAC routes after all VLAN members
 are removed from a VLAN, which should not happen.
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

**Expected Behavior**:
When the last member is removed from a VLAN that has EVPN enabled (VLAN-VNI mapping), the following should occur:
1. VLAN member state status should be set to notok
2. The Linux VNI netdevice should be brought DOWN
3. FRR/Zebra should detect the VNI netdevice DOWN state
4. BGP should withdraw all EVPN Type-2 (MAC) routes for that VNI
5. Peer EVPN nodes should remove the withdrawn routes

**Actual Behavior**:
MAC routes continue being advertised even after all VLAN members are removed.

**Root Cause Analysis**:
After reviewing the [SONiC EVPN VXLAN HLD](https://github.com/sonic-net/SONiC/blob/master/doc/vxlan/EVPN/EVPN_VXLAN_HLD.md) and the [L2 MAC flow diagram](https://github.com/sonic-net/SONiC/blob/master/doc/vxlan/EVPN/images/l2macflowcombined.PNG), the architecture shows:

1. **VNI netdevice creation** in Linux kernel triggers IMET route origination (Section 4.3.6)
2. **fdbsyncd** subscribes to FDB for VLANs with VLAN-VNI mappings
3. **FRR/Zebra** monitors the **Linux VNI netdevice state** (not STATE_DB!)
4. When VNI netdevice goes DOWN, FRR withdraws EVPN routes

**Two issues identified**:
1. **portsorch doesn't track VLAN member state status based on members**
   - VLAN member state status is not updated when members are added/removed
   - First member addition should set VLAN oper status UP
   - Last member removal should set VLAN oper status DOWN

2. **vxlanmgr doesn't monitor VLAN member state status**
   - vxlanmgr creates VNI netdevices when VLAN-VNI mapping exists
   - But it never monitors VLAN member changes
   - VNI netdevice stays UP even when VLAN has no members
   - FRR sees VNI netdevice as UP, continues advertising routes

```
VLAN Member Change → portsorch → STATE_DB:VLAN_TABLE → vxlanmgr → Linux VNI netdevice → FRR/Zebra → BGP EVPN
```
**Implementation**:
Fix #1: Track VLAN member state Status (portsorch)
Fix #2: Monitor VLAN member state and Control VNI Netdevice (vxlanmgr)

